text:
thank you to everyone who has sent me messages of support over these past few days.ğŸ’™ my own experience has intimately exposed me to reality of why so many survivors do not report rape to law enforcement or other authorities. 
the sheer number of heartbreaking let downs i have endured at the hand of a system lacking trauma-informed treatment, efficacy and ability to do their jobs is appalling and almost unbelievable.

all of this, all of these failings, have retraumatized me in ways i never thought possible. every time i have been devastated once again i have asked myself what i could have said or done differently to communicate the severity and my terror at the thought of a person who attacked me continuing his life without restriction or retribution of any kind. 
i have continued to withstand the doubt, the blame, the institutional betrayal in the hope that the man who raped me will not be able to hurt others and will be held accountable for his actions. i have been taking the failure of others to do their job as a representation of my inadequacy in recounting the horror he put me through that night. i haven't been able to trust a single decision i have made in this process, as how could i trust the decision making skills of a girl who trusted someone and found herself getting raped? 
but the reality is, i need to reframe and re-examine why i am doing any of this. i have gone forward with the expectation that my rapist will be held accountable and that i will get justice. and although i deserve that, i simply cannot continue to rely on that as my motivation for continuing. doing so would allow the very real possibility that there is no justice in my case to destroy me. 
i need to do this for me. i need to fight for me. i need to trust the decisions i have made as the best for myself, my safety, my mental health and my overall wellbeing. i need to trust me. i am pushing forward for the opportunity to tell my truth, out of the realization that going back now would be retracting my story, something that i simply cannot do. i am going forward because i am worthy. my truth is worthy of being told and i am worthy of action being taken in response to my trauma.

text: yesterday facebook reminded me that 4 years ago, i was a single mum going through a divorce, living in a 1.5 bedroom condo with two toddlers. iâ€™d just left the job that iâ€™d moved to toronto for (#metoo) and i was dragging myself through every. single. day. aside from my sister...i was so alone...so lost...so uninspired. // four years ago today, i almost took a job as a district manager for another fitness company in ontario...a job that i was taking to support my girls (at the expense of my spirit). i almost took that job...but then i said no to fear. // 3 years ago i was alone... and i told myself every day that i always would be... // but then i said no to fear. i said no to the fear that i couldnâ€™t own my own practice. i said no to the fear that i shouldnâ€™t spend more and more $ on continuing education. i said no to the fear that the empty warehouse studio that i chose to start energy tree wasnâ€™t the right space. i said no to the fear that my girls would resent having to spend so much time in preschool (and after school care). i said no to the fear that i would be alone forever. i said no to the fear that i might get hurt again. i said no to the fear that iâ€™d never be a mother again...and after two miscarriages...when that fear was creeping back...i said no again. // say no to fear, my loves, because, as they say, everything is on the other side of fear. everything...a whole new world. #flashbackfriday

text:
@jessc_m so when a flat chested chic writes about fashion trends. and explains her projections, jealousy and envy before she even begins the article.

profits are plunging at victoriaâ€™s secret as a proudly bra-less look takes hold. the most fashionable boobs are now no longer in your face.

the right kind of boob, by contrast, can be seen on the cover of this monthâ€™s us vogue, where lady gaga leans towards the camera in a low-cut brandon maxwell dress, her cleavage in its natural position, rather than lifted skywards. the no-bra scenario is emphasised by one of the straps of the dress falling off her shoulder. the vogue-approved cleavage is the natural kind.

right so this b*tch is attacking @victoriassecret who i follow here and who do a lot of non push up bras! and then lauds a rival. sounds like a guardian hack to me.

what's that? you appropriated lgtbq rights to sell some news for the guardian which is struggling as much as sainsbury's and or victoria secret did you. #metoo from your knees and then we can talk.

and she goes on;

see also the most famous cleavage of the instagram age. boobs donâ€™t get any more political than emily ratajkowskiâ€™s. at every stage of her journey from blurred linesâ€™ semi-naked backing dancer to prominent feminist activist, her breasts have become the story.

whenÂ she was arrested in washington dcÂ protesting against brett kavanaughâ€™s appointment a month ago, her choice of outfit â€“ a white cropped vest with no bra â€“ was deemed by many headline writers the most newsworthy element of her detainment. her friend and comrade amy schumer came to her defence, denouncing trolls who rage against â€œthe victims, or a beautiful woman youâ€™re threatened byâ€ instead of directing their anger at the perpetrators of sexual assault.

wait; first you journalist you, it's alleged, 2nd isn't that why she wore it, not wore it? or did she think she was a french fanatic extrovert, because i thought i hadn't seem her for a while.

ok.c*mgu**ler i'm not dome with you! let's go to the comments.

text:
those of you who know me in rl or on social media, know i rarely post photos that are "sexy" . i don't do much to make myself appealing *~survival instinct . . . i have posted womanly stuff on occasion, of course, and i sometimes feel sexual, but for the most part (especially recent years), i probably seem like a bit of a prude . . . childhood sexual trauma, incest, rape, three stalkers (two exes, one boss), and countless experiences of harrassment, means that being exposed in a sexual way is a significant fear of mine . so much so, that i have completely withdrawn from my sexual self and have been celibate for most of the past eight years . . . as important as the historical #metoo movement is, it means that many of us must relive old pain . but we are strong, and we are stronger *together*. . . since i was already drowning in my sea of demons, i used my pain to create a body of work titled: "my vagina is the window to your soul" . (my words to the men who have debased me; the art my visceral response) : paintings, digital collage, and sculptural construct . . . i have had a difficult few years with acute flareups of complex-ptsd and autoimmune dysfunction (connected in the whole health model since all are dysfunction of the central nervous system) . . . anyways, i am working on stepping out of my comfort zone . . . this private photo is from a boudoir shoot a few years ago . it may seem tame to some, but it is risque for me . . . nervous posting, but i am working on healing the deeper part of myself that holds my darkest secrets and shame . my heart is pounding with anxiety as i acknowledge my sexual self and share it . . . exhibition 2019 : studio57 . time will tell how it unfolds . . . until then, if you are interested in viewing this body of work online, please visit: www.myvaginaisthewindowtoyoursoul.ca .
i appreciate your support of my art . it is healing . i wish love & healing for you too â¤ #myvaginaisthewindowtoyoursoul #rape #rapeculture #healingtogether #artofhealing #nlartist #nlarts #feminism #selflove #selfcare #cptsd #metoo #ibelieveyou #timesup #vanetyfabrick

text: are you a college student? education secretary betsy devos is proposing a troubling overhaul to the way colleges handle complaints of sexual misconduct. the education department released a plan that would require schools to investigate sexual assault and harassment only if the alleged misconduct was reported to certain campus officials and only if it occurred on campus or other areas overseen by the school. the plan would narrow the definition of sexual assault and harassment and allow students accused of misconduct to cross-examine accusers in campus hearings. devosâ€™ proposal would replace obama-era guidelines she scrapped last year, saying they were unfair to students accused of sexual misconduct. this is not right. it erases the voices of survivors, places perpetrators at the center of title ix, and allows schools to further get away with not giving survivors the justice they need and deserve. hands off title ix! check out @endrapeoncampus for advocacy tools! #titleix #metoo #metoomovement [image description: a series of words arranged in different shaped triangles stating no person in the united states shall be, on the basis of sex, be excluded from participation in, be denied the benefits of, or be subjected to discrimination under any education program or activity receiving federal financial assistance]

text:
education secretary betsy devos on friday released new proposed regulations on how schools should handle sexual assault that will give more benefit of doubt to the accused and walk back obama-era directives that critics said were unfair to men.

the proposals, which would affect the way schools must interpret the federal title ix gender equity law, were months in the making and contained some major surprises, including a new requirement that colleges conduct live hearings for sexual assault cases. #metoo #maga #obama #trump #billcosby #betsydevos

text:
i'll start as the columnist started with critique. jewish and ghanaian, married ghanaian. her jewish grandfather graduates from cambridge. born norway. worked as social affairs editor and education editor at rupert murdoch's sky for 3 years 14-17 before defecting to the now increasingly leftist guardian.

i'm not done, ghana along with ivory coast and nigeria, responsible for capturing and enslaving their east african cousins and selling them to slavers. ask a black person about the generalisation of trusting persons of these demographics. yes i generalised. but within the context of what comes before. elevation of status seems to be something common in her heritage. did the guardian pull out the whitest black person they had for this one? i's it one of those most deadly types of racism. the i have black friends kind? no you have a black person you know from the office kind. or when you actually want to let your hair down you go out with the black girl who knows some other black girls kind. i wonder is her social group predominantly white? it's usually a staple for progression at oxford.

she begins.

text:
a gathering of deep longings, 
finally, 
breaking dawn of desires 
locked in your sour embrace 
erupting bodies of buried fires
i am drowning in the rapture of a fatal kiss
trembling with fear of those intoxicated sultry eyes
i know you're evading my soul 
but my lips utter "highly obliged"! ~ was it your love  i know not  for love makes people whole  unlikely,  made me deprived  of my own soul!

text: a day late to national coming out day, but here i am - bisexual & queer and proud. queer because i am attracted to both women (cis, trans, nonbinary) and men (cis, trans, nonbinary), and i am a cisgender woman, but i am fluid in my presentation, so queer is the word i like to use. i also like that it used to be a pejorative thatâ€™s now been reclaimed. i have been out since may 2015. itâ€™s not something you do once and get over with. i have to keep coming out to people all the time because cishet is the norm and people assume i am cishet. i am grateful to live in los angeles where i am free to be me. i hope my fellow queers around the world, in countries like russia, saudi arabia, uganda, iraq, iran, honduras, egypt, and nigeria will enjoy this freedom one day soon. i hope the homophobes in my countries (us & canada) will come to the realisation that it is so much easier to fill yourself with love than to rot away from hate. love is love. happy #nationalcomingoutday ğŸ³ï¸â€ğŸŒˆ

text:
cw: the following post and article discuss verbal, physical and sexual trauma.

since the 13 reasons why tv series was first released i have wanted to share my thoughts on the book - which i first read as a teen -and itâ€™s adaptation. through the youth mental health website, @speakthewordscom i am thankful to have an opportunity to share my thoughts and experience.  as someone who was bullied as a child and deals with trauma, the book and show created a lot of conflicting feelings for me. i was glad to see such issues be spoken about in so many public spheres. however there are many undeniable missteps in both the book and showâ€™s approaches to appropriate representation of these sensitive topics. one of the real life assaults at st. michaelâ€™s college school in toronto that came out in the media this week, eerily mirrored the most contentious scene of the 2nd season of 13rw. there is a long held history of silencing around these types of assaults and while i think 13rw had good intentions to shed light on them, that doesnâ€™t make up for the fact its portrayal was needlessly graphic and potentially triggering for many people.  besides assault portrayals, the way that mental health issues are addressed on the show seems to be an afterthought, when there was the opportunity to show healing and therapeutic discussions and strategies to a wide audience.  for this piece i got to interview @summerscourtney who is a ya author who writes about similar issues in much more sensitively nuanced ways that arenâ€™t harmful or exploitive. the link to the article and interview with courtney summers are in my profile bio.

text: day 16 of 23 days of thanks. thank you to southern indiana volunteers of the year, marianne conrad and scott minton. marianne has supported our non-residential and residential clients. through referrals via the phone and every other week she dedicates office hours in our office space at sic. through her work clients have been helped with evictions, immigration services, divorces among other services she has been able to give our clients reassurance that someone is on their side. scott minton has been a valued member of the sipc for several years.  he has been instrumental in own it and menâ€™s work, fundraising and community event planning and has connected the center with multiple supports, donors and partners over the years.  itâ€™s clear that scottâ€™s passion is getting men engaged in the work we do so that they are part of the solution to ending violence.  he has mentioned on more than one occasion that his daughters are the reason he is committed to this work.  ensuring that they grow up in a safe and nurturing community is one of his top priorities.  we are forever grateful that scott has chosen to be a part of the center and our mission to end violence.

text:
day 4 of #nakedwerise is play. â€œhow do you heal creatively? how can you break out something to wear today that feels risky yet brings out more of your true nature and makes you feel more alive while you determine your sense of safety?â€â€¢
dance and sex are probably the things i do most that involve this element of healing play. sometimes yoga as well but my yoga practice has become less fun and more stale over the years (something iâ€™d like to rectify). things that put me in my body in a conscious way, that have creativity involved. â€¢
as far as clothes, this is definitely an area where i like to experiment and express myself. i love having fun with how i dress and i love to feel sexy sometimes too. for myself and for my husband. but i donâ€™t like receiving attention from other men and it always makes me uncomfortable. i wish two things - that men would learn to keep their comments to themselves, and that i could feel safe wearing what i want no matter what. i wish that for all women/femmes actually, i want the world to be a safe place for our self expression. â€¢
â€¢
â€¢

text: so many exciting things in the works for #ibelievethem. literally giddy to launch the platform and show you all what we are working on! check out the link in bio and click the "donate" button to read a full description of what we are working on! thank you all so much for the kind words of support for the project, and to everyone that has donated so far to help us with our friends and family pre-fund. if you want to get involved in any way, shoot us a dm or email! content contributions, op-ed columns, resource sharing, story sharing, merch campaigns, you name it! this is going to be an insanely ambitious community effort that gets at all sides of this issue. we have already established some awesome partnerships with campaign strategists, educators, legal experts, advocates, and other non-profits working to eliminate the culture of sexual discrimination and abuse as well as provide an all-in-one safe space network for survivors and allies to connect with one another and share the healing journey. together, we will take the watershed moment of #metoo to the next step to drive collective action. sharing your journey is the first step in bringing attention to the issues at hand. we love you, we believe in you, and we believe you. thanks for taking this leap of faith with us, and keep an eye out for some big changes to the account once we launch. wooohoooo let's go!!! #ibelievethem #believesurvivors #timesup #metoo #allies #raiseyourvoice #shoutyourabuse #change #sharegoodness #share #ibelieveyou #imwithher #intersectionalfeminism #lgbtq #believewomen #endrape #womensrights #transrightsarehumanrights #nohate #pinkwave

text:
"i am 35 now but ever since i was 18, i have always had some relatively unique physical preferences in the women i became sexual with. at a young age - before sex was even a thought to me - i unfortunately experienced some sexual trauma which eventually shaped my current physical preference.
-
when i engage in sex with a woman, her grooming habits have become a make-or-break issue for me. i get turned on by a woman who doesn't shave and goes au naturel. i'm sure some of it is also because i used to steal my mom and dad's 70s and 80s porn back in the day and the women then rocked some serious bush. but this has become such a thing for me that if i get involved with a woman sexually and she is shaved or even trimmed, i can't maintain an erection.
-
i'm already very particular when it comes to sex. i will not engage in the act unless there is a deeper connection than what is on the surface.Â i dated a woman once, we meshed really well, and i was convinced she was the one. we began to get intimate and then i noticed she was shaved. i tried to ignore it, but it was so much of an issue that i lost my erection and couldn't get it back up. we talked about it, and i had to reassure her that she did nothing wrong.Â i eventually went to therapy where i learned that my sexual trauma from my childhood had a lot more to do with it than i had expected.
-
unfortunately, in today's society it is practically frowned upon for women to have body hair - which i also find ridiculous, despite my preference - but it has made dating a bit problematic. i've learned to be a little more transparent about my preference, especially when the conversation of sex comes up. but i've noticed that so many women frown upon it and i've become pretty isolated, especially when it comes to dating or meeting others. i get tired of being looked at as being weird or disgusting for having such a preference."
name: Lets Talk About Sex. For Real.

text:
when i was 17, i was in a relationship with this guy who was a few years older than me. he would call me on the phone just to pick on me, he would shame me for my (somewhat normal) body size and put me down for having ambitions and goals for my life. he was an a**, really and not very intelligent, i might add.
.
on one occasion after we broke up, he got physical with me because i didnâ€™t want to hear him out (and this happened several times during our relationship, too)
.
still, i felt like the one who had lost something for quite a while after our breakup. because i didnâ€™t feel like i deserved better than what he could give me. because i was bigger than the average girl (woman) my age. because i thought i had to lose weight to really deserve love.
.
i thought i loved him.
.
i still feel sick to my stomach when i see this dumb f**k on the street or when i pass him in my car. not because iâ€™m in any way afraid of him (heâ€™s tiny and he would probably die, if i sat on him), but because he reminds me of what used to be. how much i used to hate myself. how badly i would allow other people to treat me, because i didnâ€™t feel like i was enough.
.
at the age of 28, i know(!!!) that this kind of behavior is unacceptable and disgusting and that i shouldnâ€™t accept anything but the absolute best for myself. i know that my body size is in no way an excuse for anyone being abusive towards me. not mentally, not physically... not sexually!
.
i deserve the very best for my life and so do you ğŸ’•

text: trust me, i know how scary it can be to be a lone opinion in a room full of people who are against you. first, i work with men and women who use physical abuse as a means to control, so usually my tools and techniques are not of popular opinion. secondly, my best friend and i have differing political beliefs, which includes her family whom i'm very close to. third, i was a "popular" cheerleader in high school who chose to be nice to others due to my parents good influence and honestly the influence of many other good people around me. it's safe to say that many of my friends felt like i did and were inclusive of others which is such an awesome thing to say about your school. with that said though, there were many times that me and a group of other individuals or just me alone were standing up to others who were trying to bully. these instances probably paved the way for my ability to stand up for what is right. however, it's not easy. it's frustrating, nerve wracking, and sometimes even dangerous. but that doesn't change how much it's worth it. the look on a kid's face when someone steps on his side, the instant that a person who abuses decides to make a different choice, the change that social justice can bring to the world are all beautiful reasons why it's important to continue to stand up for what is right. silence is often enabling the wrong. did you know that women are told to yell "fire!" when being sexually attacked by a man because you are more likely to get help for a fire than a rape? this has got to stop. we need to stand together and help each other. silence is deadly. letting someone continually get away with bad behavior/criminal behavior does nothing for our society. call people out. stand up for others. do the right thing. #hykelyfe #bestlyfe #standup #bully #dotherightthing #standalone #socialjustice #rape #sexualassault #fire #abuse #silenceisdeadly #callthemout #metoo #mentalillness #mentalhealth #therapy
name: HykeLyfe, LLC / BestLyfe

text_retweet:
goosebumps. 
thank you amazing @aijiaofficial and to all the women you gathered for this 
#repost @aijiaofficial
ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
i have something personal to share... this year has felt like a particularly hard year to be a woman to me. so many people i knew were sharing their stories online of sexual assault and abuse, and i found myself shying away from social media. it hurt to read yet another story of harassment or abuse.  what's sad is that i wasn't shocked by it, i was just worn down. and yet through this breaking open, a quiet solidarity formed; a holding of space for people to share their stories. a community was being born. this roaring back of survivors saying, "that happened to me too, and i believe you." it was a place for healing. â€”
sexual abuse and assault are happening to women, men, and gender non-conforming people all over the world. it does not discriminate by ethnicity, class, or political affiliation. this is a human issue. a little over a month ago i watched dr. christine blasey-ford's testimony along with the rest of the country. i don't know her. i don't know her alleged attacker. i wasn't there. but her story sounded very familiar to me. i recognized the quiver in her voice. i was sick to my stomach. and i couldn't sleep. i finally got up in the middle of the night, sat at the piano and put my feelings on paper. afterwards i felt better and went to bed at peace. the next day i went in studio with my dear friend @jameyjaz and recorded what i had written, which turned out to be this song. the following day i found the visionary and director of this project, @vanessabeletic. and now a month later, here we are debuting the music video, which was unlike any experience i've ever had. â€”
to the brave survivors and allies who gave of their time to bare their souls in this video, thank you. you owned your power and i am so humbled that i was there to witness it. it was a day of transformation. â€”
i stand with anyone who has experienced sexual or domestic assault of any kind. i believe you. i am your tribe. there are others too. for those who are afraid to come forward. for those who chose to speak up only to be shut down. you are not alone. i wrote this #foryou
name: F equals

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
the other side||lacy m. johnson||â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸
â€¢
â€¢
[thank you to the author for this #giftedbook. i am beyond grateful]
lacy m. johnson is a force. she makes words make sense. she makes meaning where answers seem impossible. her words are specific and left in the right places, without feeling tedious or over worked. the other side is in one instance clinical and poetry in the next. this book has balance.
â€¢
â€¢
reliving and articulating an unthinkable trauma is where this book starts. but it is a lot more. it is about the body, relationships, memories, motherhood, vengeance, love, grief and more and more and more. it is not sensational. it is too specific to be gratuitous. it is a very good book.
â€¢
â€¢
you should know this book is full of triggers (rape, emotional & physical abuse). johnson handles the trauma with dignity, but it is still trauma. if you can, i recommend this book. itâ€™s not for everyone. it certainly was for me. iâ€™m grateful to have read it.
â€¢
â€¢
have you read this? what did you think? super excited to check out the reckonings now.
â€¢
â€¢
i have a more detailed review on the blog. link in bio. check it out.

text:
education secretary betsy devos has finally released her rewrite of rules for campus sexual harassment and assault allegations, narrowing the cases schools must investigate and which results in giving the accused more rights. 
schools will have to let an accused person cross-examine their accuser via third party, and will be able to use higher standards of evidence to decide guilt. they will not need to investigate reports of any off-campus sexual assaults involving their students. "the goal is to basically reduce the obligation of schools to address sexual harassment," said elizabeth tang, an attorney at the national women's law center. "what the department is doing is inviting schools to ignore sexual harassment." the regulations will not go into effect right away, and could possibly change. the proposal is going through a governmental process known as "notice and comment." it has been printed in the federal register, and now, any member of the public has 60 days to submit their opinion about the proposed rules in writing to the education department.

a covert narcissist knows how to play nice, charming, funny, and just an all around good person. some will even go as far as being extremely generous to others with their time and money.
.
.
then behind closed doors, he or she will be the meanest, most vile and abusive person; totally different from the person they present to everyone else.
.
.
they know what they're doing. this is done deliberately so that if the person they're abusing ever tells anyone what's happening - it will seem virtually unbelievable, and people will say, "there's no way he (or she) would ever do such a thing." ğŸ’¯
.

question: the american film industry has undergone a lot of change over the past year in the wake of the #metoo movement, which has since spread to many parts of the world. the korean industry had a fervent #metoo period, and now bollywood, just over the past couple of weeks, has seen #metoo allegations against prominent directors and producers. but the movement hasnâ€™t really come to japan much. why do you think that is? do women in the japanese industry face these same injustices that have been exposed in the u.s., and do you think change is needed here too? .
.

answer: tough question! i think the problem pertains not only to the film industry, because i have many friends working in other industries. i do feel that many people have been hurt and bruised â€” not only women, but many men as well â€” by both words and actions. it seems that, perhaps, there are many people here who are very good at pretending not to see or not to notice. so i presume that many have to face these struggles alone, internally. if film can perhaps help serve to acknowledge these struggles and offer at least some soothing remedy, that would be a very good thing.

text:
mom, i feel awkward, i feel lost,
the thing between my legs,
makes me, qualm over my dress and walk.
i understand your reinsure,
that i will cope up and learn to bear.
but i donâ€™t understand grannyâ€™s distress,
for now, she vexingly sees me as stress.
repeating over and over about things to be of aware.
you say those crimson dots have turned me into a butterfly,
but arenâ€™t butterflies supposed to fly free in the air?
how will i cope up with the crimson dots, who turned me into a butterfly?
i feel more like a malady, to be in a coop and cared.
you say they are innocuous, so do not fret,
but they whisper into my ears,
itâ€™s time to forgo your innocence and stay into a shell.
for now, you will enter the masculine fancy
and become a prey to their carnal covet.
- monica gupta

text:
"and we will be heard..." song of the caged bird is out now! download/stream on all your favorites.

i'm currently listening on @spotify and @googleplaymusic 
a huge thank you to everyone involved in this project. i wish y'all could have seen me freaking out in my car writing this just being amped up about the power this song can have. i don't know that i have ever been more proud of a piece of my work.

jim reilley thank you so very much for believing in this song and believing in me. it was so wonderful creating this song with you!  i cant wait to do more music together!

eric fritsch at eastwood recording studio for all the work you did recording, creating and mixing. and of course barney the amazing barn/studio cat for all the purrs and meows.

rob shollenberger of sound pallet studios for editing and mastering (and humoring me when i pestered you about needing to know if my vocals were spot on or not)

amanda comerford for being a lovely friend and for creating something i am so proud to display as the cover art!

my heart y'all, i am just so thankful.

photo cred: candice ruth

text:
so, i've been on a personal crusade recently.  i attempted to press charges for one of my assaults.  in the process i discovered my assailant is dead and has been for a very long time.  for years i talked with friends and family about doing this and was always talked out of it for "my protection". if one person had just said, "you know what?  if you want to, i'm with you," i would have found out about his death and lived the last 20 years of my life without fear, and without so much worry and guilt about who he could be hurting. 
#mindfulwalkphotography #selfportrait #ptsd #mentalhealthawareness #metoo #ibelievevictims #fuckdepressionğŸ–•

text:
good read but letâ€™s also remember our sons donâ€™t owe anyone a hug either ğŸ’š

via: girlscouts.org

holidays and family get-togethers are a time for yummy food, sweet traditions, funny stories, and lots and lots of love. but they could, without you even realizing it, also be a time when your daughter gets the wrong idea about consent and physical affection.

have you ever insisted, â€œuncle just got hereâ€”go give him a big hug!â€ or â€œauntie gave you that nice toy, go give her a kiss,â€ when you were worried your child might not offer affection on her own? if yes, you might want to reconsider the urge to do that in the future.

think of it this way, telling your child that she owes someone a hug either just because she hasnâ€™t seen this person in a while or because they gave her a gift can set the stage for her questioning whether she â€œowesâ€ another person any type of physical affection when theyâ€™ve bought her dinner or done something else seemingly nice for her later in life. â€œthe notion of consent may seem very grown-up and like something that doesnâ€™t pertain to children,â€ says girl scoutsâ€™ developmental psychologist dr. andrea bastiani archibald, â€œbut the lessons girls learn when theyâ€™re young about setting physical boundaries and expecting them to be respected last a lifetime, and can influence how she feels about herself and her body as she gets older. plus, sadly, we know that some adults prey on children, and teaching your daughter about consent early on can help her understand her rights, know when lines are being crossed, and when to go to you for help.â€ give your girl the space to decide when and how she wants to show affection. of course, many children may naturally want to hug and kiss family members, friends, and neighbors, and thatâ€™s lovelyâ€”but if your daughter is reticent, consider letting her choose what to do.

full article: https://www.girlscouts.org/en/raising-girls/happy-and-healthy/happy/what-is-consent.html#

text:
#respetonaman is a nationwide campaign against gender-based violence. as inspired by the global #metoo, and #timesup movement and thailandâ€™s #donttellmehowtodress movement, it will focus on bringing the issue into the mainstream and empowering women to rise up against all forms of gender-based violence.

in line with this year's 16-days of activism against gender-based violence, #respetonaman will hold a series of events and programs which would include two big forums, an online campaign, and a philippine version of the #donttellmehowtodress exhibit.

#respetonaman is a project of vice president maria leonor â€œleniâ€ robredo, un women, the embassy of sweden in manila, spark! philippines, and empower; supported by don'ttellmehowtodress thailand, cindy bishop, bdo, sanggunian ng mga paaralang loyola ng ateneo de manila university, office of social concern and involvement of ateneo de manila university, and power plant mall.

text:
"despite our need to simplify and generalize... humans are intrinsically impossible to simplify. we are never just good or just bad. we are mosaics of our best selves and our worst selves, our deepest secrets and our favorite stories to tell at a dinner party, existing somewhere between our well-lit profile photo and our drivers license shot. we are all a mixture of selfishness and generosity, loyalty and self-preservation, pragmatism and impulsiveness." day 109/100: taylor swift 
#100daysofaweinspiringwomen
caption below written by dear friend and tay tay loving partner in crime, @alysonturley .
taylor alison swift (born december 13, 1989) is an american singer-songwriter, performer, philanthropist, and recently, political activist. known for her narrative, highly personal and emotive style of songwriting, swift secured her first record deal at 14. she has since built an estimated net worth of $320 million, released 5 platinum albums, which sold a combined 40+ million copies, produced 5 number one and 22 top ten hit songs, and won 23 awards, including 10 grammys. swift has often made headlines through her romantic relationships and become a controversial figure despite avoiding the problems that commonly follow early fame. taylor swift has donated millions of dollars to education, music programs, sexual violence survivor funds and disaster relief, making her consistently one of the most charitable celebrities in the country. swift is also recognized as part of the #metoo movement, famously winning a sexual assault lawsuit, and landing on the cover of time magazine along with other women driving the movement. she maintains an active social media presence, through which she engages her devoted fan base. in october 2018, she used this platform to break her long time silence on politics and express support for the lgbt community, racial minorities, and gender equality, and encourage her followers to vote, especially in her home state of tennessee. - -
-
-
-

text:
itâ€™s fearless friday!  this pic is really old yet i keep it propped up by my desk as a reminder that i can do things even if theyâ€™re scary.
.
this pic was taken in ixtapa right after i went parasailing.  i had been watching others do it for a few days and wanted to try it because it looked really cool, but i hesitated because it also looked scary.  i would have to trust the boat driver to not take me too far out, iâ€™d have to trust that my landing would be safe, iâ€™d have to trust that there wouldnâ€™t be any sharks when i landed....i remember waiting in line and almost left the line a few times.  i was scared.  this was something new to me, it was unknown, and it was something i would have no control over once i was in the air.
.
i loved it!!! the view was breathtaking.  i felt free.  it was relaxing and exhilarating at the same time.  i didnâ€™t want my time in the air to end.  i was sooo glad i stayed in line and waited my turn.  i was so glad i didnâ€™t let my fears take over and get the best of me.  how disappointing it would have been to have missed this experience.
.
when iâ€™m stepping in the unknown, trying something new, needing to trust myself or others, not being able to control a situation and needing to go with the flow, i look at this picture and remember i can do it, i can trust myself and my intuition, i donâ€™t need to have the control or know the outcome in advance, and that sometimes things we really want are a little scary.
.
take a moment today to think about what fear is holding you back.  how can you move forward and not let your fear(s) set you back?  have a great day - itâ€™s friday! ğŸ’œ

text:
cover reveal for jared yates sextonâ€™s the man they wanted me to be is here! â–ªï¸ available in may and not one moment too soon, the author of the people are going to rise upon your shore turns his keen eye to our current crisis of masculinity using his upbringing in a rural, patriarchal home as an entry point to consider the personal and societal dangers of performative gender.
â–ªï¸
based on his provocative and popular new york times op-ed, the man they wanted me to be is both memoir and cultural analysis. jared yates sexton alternates between an examination of his working class upbringing and historical, psychological, and sociological sources that examine the genesis of toxic masculinity and its consequences for society. â–ªï¸
as progressivism changes american society, and globalism shifts labor away from traditional manufacturing, the roles that have been prescribed to men since the industrial revolution have been rendered as obsolete. donald trump's campaign successfully leveraged male resentment and entitlement, and now, with trump as president and the rise of the #metoo movement, itâ€™s clearer than ever what a problem performative masculinity is. â–ªï¸
deeply personal and thoroughly researched, the man they wanted me to be examines how we teach boys whatâ€™s expected of men in america, and the long term effects of that socializationâ€•which include depression, suicide, misogyny, and, ultimately, shorter lives. sexton turns his keen eye to the establishment of the racist patriarchal structure which has favored white men, and investigates the personal and societal dangers of such outdated definitions of manhood.

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
#metoo as an example of social mediaâ€™s power. ğŸ“±
ğŸ’¡ you may not know that, but â€œme tooâ€ is something that was created way before the 2017 scandals about sexual assault. in 2006, tarana burke used that phrase for the first time on her â€œmyspaceâ€ to support and empower women of color who faced sexual violence. [6]
in 2017, alyssa milano encouraged people to use the # to share their stories when celebrities started to share theirs about harvey weinstein. [https://twitter.com/alyssa_milano/status/919659438700670976]
â¡ï¸ how can we explain that the metoo movement became known only in 2017 when it started 10 years before? my hypothesis:

text:
early morning thoughts. sharing because somebody needs this. from my heart to yours â¤ï¸ i never have expectations of people. i just simply go with the flow. people change sometimes and not always for the better but i'm never surprised. now when the change is something you can no longer deal with, you have a choice to make for you because you better believe that they are gonna or have already made their choice regarding you. good thing is every loss will bring you something even better. for me a loss has always turned out to be a blessing. trust me! i know first hand. stop forcing it. life is too short to not be totally and completely happy. we all deserve it! dont think that it doesn't exist because your with someone at the present time who can't give it to you. get to your happy! it's urgent like a mofoâ€¼ï¸ some people are just stuck in their ways but everybody ain't gonna/have to deal with that. love should make you want to evolve and grow and do certain things different for the right person. if it isn't making you happy, making you better or making you money, then why would you want it in your space? sometimes it may get better, perhaps it's a phase, life events etc but you know in your heart what it is truely. that you can't deny. i love you! your amazing! we all deserve the best! don't ever second guest that! â¤ï¸ #lovemovement  #lovetrumpshate365 #playwright #host #brandambassador #healer #actress #activist #motivationalspeaker #domesticviolence #rape #abuse #metoo

text:
"the music always comes in my darkest hour, and the music is always so giving. i have this picture of an endless well somewhere, i don't know where it is -- in the star systems out there. and the more that you're open to it the more that it keeps coming."
it's hard to believe it was on this day 9 years ago i first met the incredible @toriamos and handed her this. it was at the time, along with a handwritten letter, the only way i knew how to express my gratitude for the ways her music had changed my life. i first heard winter when i was 11; was drawn to the angst of caught a lite sneeze & spark in my teens; and fell in love with a sorta fairytale and scarlet just before my 18th... it wasn't until i was almost 25 that her music really hit home on a deeper level. but tori has always been a lighthouse and given a voice to the things that mattered... for 15 years before the #metoo movement, she was giving people the courage to find their own voice and healing, through her music, words and presence. i don't know where i'd be without her music, words, wisdom, courage, kindness, compassion and empathy, but i sure as hell wouldn't be who i am and where i am today. and wouldn't have met some of the incredible people all around the world that i have. endlessly grateful is an understatement. â™¥ï¸ğŸ¶â™¥ï¸ğŸ¶â™¥ï¸

whenever an act of violence hits swedish society, everything slows down. we go to school and work, we drop our kids of at daycare, we pick up the groceries. but there is this somber mood alerting us to the fact that something has changed. we felt it after our foreign minister anna lind was murdered in 2001, after the tsunami in 2004, after the terrorist attacks in trollhÃ¤ttan and on drottningsgatan. menâ€™s everyday violence does not normally generate these reactions. itâ€™s too common, too accepted. but during those days in november, it happened. we finally started treating sexual violence as a major threat to our society. for a brief moment, the power structure shifted. the men who had continuously caused fear, were now the ones who were afraid. not afraid of violence, of course. to my knowledge, there has not been a single reported incident of a woman sexually assaulting a man as retaliation for something that was brought up during metoo. that power structure is still very much intact. but some men got to be afraid of criticism, of social stigma, of having to change their behavior or face the economic and legal consequences.

beacuse you are afraid of our amazingÂ abilit(ies)

but we burn them all to flames.

one by one,

from time to time.

we hold the magic in our bones,

and let me tell you there is nothing there out in this universe which can put us down on hold.

when there has been our need,

and walked on the face of the earth zealously, Â paying any heed to each and every being.

you can callÂ us whatever you want,

because that only tell us what we are upÂ against. 
o woman ! o man ! 
the time has come for us again,

to rise from the ashes of the fire that they light,

to free the world from the chains of itsÂ ownÂ misery like as we have always did.

by being true to our own bid.

mgtow 101: the new slave master

let's examine the psychology of the black woman in america. they don't live in the same america the black male does. they have a whole different perception of this country than we do. they can get away with so many things, that they have turned lawless. most truly believe they own the man all due to the laws and government. look at how she kills the man like his slave master and takes off.

the enemy of your enemy is your ally, seems to be the motto they live by as it pertains to black men. they can remove you from your home, put you on child support, get you locked up, kill you and even kill your kids by burning them in an oven, if you don't get off work and baby sit them.

this society views them as a sex object yet views the black man as a threat, so they will never see america or the world the way we do. even back in slavery they saw a different america than the men. without the system the average black woman in america would be in trouble, from the educated gods, to the welfare gods.

when a shootout gets labeled a drug beef in the hood, many times its two drug dealers beefing because they both share a baby mama or girlfriend.

when a man is in jail for child support who put him there?

when a man is in prison for domestic violence, who has provoked him for years, hitting him with no consequences until he snaps and hits back, and she calls the police?

when a man is selling drugs who benefits the most from the thug simp? his mother, that stays quiet if he pays the bills, strippers and non black businesses.

this is a discussion that's way past due, but may never happen because we have simps in 2018 venerating the black woman as god on earth. as the woman said in that older post, the government empowers the woman to take down the man and breakup the family. not just so the mother benefits, but so the government can indoctrinate and program the kids.

they send her to work, and they abandon their kids, leaving them in schools taught by racist, pedophiles, liberals and satanist. i see it clearly as day, i'm wondering when other black men will realize, that the black woman is the new slave master and satan's most lethal soldier.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
misha* was sexually abused and assaulted by a 17-year-old boy in her community. the police registered a case and the boy was kept under arrest for a few days and no action was taken beyond that. 
however, world vision indiaâ€™s child protection unit (cpu) stepped in and asked mishaâ€™s mother to call the childline. the childline immediately took over the case and the boy is now imprisoned in a juvenile jail. the cpu not only helped misha get assistance from childline, but also helped the family receive a compensation from the government. 
cpus in the 6200 communities we serve play an important role for attaining the overall well-being of children by strengthening the system and structures at various levels.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

.
gender-based violence adalah sebuah isu yang harus kita bicarakan dan bantu hentikan bersama-sama. ayo ikut suarakan keresahanmu tentang isu ini di @enambelasffest selama 16 hari anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan mulai 25 november ini!
.
kegiatan ini merupakan bagian dari gerakan global yang dipimpin oleh un women untuk menghentikan gender-based violence. jadi yuk kita sama-sama berkontribusi dengan mengedukasi diri lebih melalui screening dan diskusi yang bakal diselanggarain oleh #enambelasffest ///
.

text: hey people, with their noses in other peoples business, the rule is, unless somebody asks for your advice 3 times you should shut up. almost every day, middle aged men, who donâ€™t have their own business, rarely spend much money in my business and sound really boring want to offer unsolicited â€œconstructive criticismâ€. i even get phone calls, usually in the middle of the day, when my restaurant is the busiest, from some guy who wants to chat and give me advice: â€œi think i need to tell you what you are doing wrong.â€ â€œyou should offer movie nights, you should turn the lights down.â€ or even worse they want to throw in their psychological evaluation of me as well? wtf?  is this what #metoo is like when you get older? i used to think, you have to listen to your critics, they might have a point.â€ well now i say fuck critics and fuck their point too...there is never anything constructive about it. if someone is giving you a backhanded compliment because they think you should stay humble and donâ€™t think you are â€œall thatâ€ itâ€™s because you are â€œall thatâ€ and they are jealous and their little ego is threatened. donâ€™t even try to explain your point of view to people who donâ€™t get you, the suggestion box is now a paper shredder. forgive them and go on being fabulous youğŸ’•

text:
what an honor it was to spend the day w/so many amazing people @risingabovefest @regallalive! it wouldn't have been possible w/o my partner #lalivefilmfestival!!! @bighousela 
i got to meet so many amazing filmmakers, attendees, sponsors, & press. heard many statements of being empowered! saw old friends & my parents got to be on their 1st red carpet. @girlupliftersteam was beyond uplifting for the future! sat on a panel w/such distinguished women, 1/2 of whom i'd just met for the event & am honored to welcome them as friends (fyi...in pic, yes i'm tall but not that tall! had to sit on a different chair so they all could have the comfy 1'sğŸ˜). spoke on a filmmaker q&a about @6feetabovemovie & @thekarmaofhappiness. hosted by @bodybygia who did a great job.

thank you to everyone who came & my wonderful team: staff & volunteers who i would've never survived w/o!

i've taken away so much from this event but 1 thing is that the haters will flock to bring you down when you're doing something good & you just have to keep "rising above!" just like the peacock, turn the poison into nectar & don't let them steal the magic. we all can help change the world if we are willing to focus on others happiness not only our own. i've fought the fight & will continue to do so, not only because of my drive & determination, but because it's the right thing to do! #neveroutofthefight

text:
sneak a peek into one of next year's releases! are you born a woman.. or do you become one? can men ever truly be feminists? and do we still need feminism in the 21st century? this book answers these questions and many more by exploring the struggle for equality that stretches back through the centuries. 
trace the subject from its origins, through the suffrage campaigns of the late 19th century, to recent developments such as the everyday sexism project and the #metoo movement. examine the ideas that underpin feminist thought through crucial figures, from simone de beauvoir to chimamanda ngozi adichie, and discover the wider social, cultural, and historical context of their impact. .
.
.

text:
there are currently 3 billion social media users worldwide. 1 billion from instagram. this means that over a third of the worldâ€™s population is using some form of social media to communicate, making social media marketing an imperative tactic for boosting leads.
so here is how it has changed the way we communicate.
1. it has created a sense of urgency and a need to share. 
now we have a need to share something with our audience. 
our audience have become our besties because why tell one person at a time when you can multiple people at once.
2. it has revolutionized word of mouth marketing;  before we had to tell someone to tell anyone but now, when a client feels good, they can post it up and help increase sales.
3. it has provided a perspective on faraway places; with the era of live streaming, the world is in our huts. now someone in faraway america can recognize girls in borno state. we can start our challenge, stop a movement by just saying #metoo 
4. we can now share our stories ourselves instead of just highlights. we can now revolutionize the way we think because i can be in nigeria but i am serving the world.
5. it has made messages so personal; now we can tell stories and make the dm personal. we can ensure that we grow relationships and find ways to be more personable.
6. it brought news back to the millennials; lots of people donâ€™t like the news but when we have pages like instablog giving news in a creative way, we stay glued.
now you know all this, how do you plan to ensure you use it to get ready for 2019?

text: saw this flyer last night about an upcoming rally by pop mob, short for popular mobilization, which is â€œa group of concerned portlanders united around a single, common goal: inspiring people to show up and resist the alt-right.â€ this group of activists and organizers aims to stop the rise of discrimination and hate groups in portland. according to @splcenter hate crimes around the country have increased by 20% since the election of trump. @popmobpdx is organizing a march for this saturday, nov. 17th, 12-3pm at chapman square, to support and raise the voices of survivors. â€not everyone is able to share their story. some survivors choose to stay silent for their safety, others are silenced by those around them. some survivors refuse to be silent. the alt-right is trying to silence survivors, erase trans identities, control the bodies of women and poc, and criminalize families and individuals seeking safety.  we are all survivors...join us on november 17th, as one strong, fierce, community coming together to amplify the voices of survivors who break the silence and share their stories. stand in solidarity with survivors as we show the country, that we will not back down we will not shut up, and we will not be erased!â€ #survivorsareeverywhere #believesurvivors #metoo #protecttransrights #blacklivesmatter

text:
#metoo movement. 
a friend made a comment yesterday. he said it has became so big because it is relatable but it is toward negativity. 
is it true? i donâ€™t know. i have been thinking since. i canâ€™t agree no more... it is relatable. however, i donâ€™t think it is toward negativity. yes rape or sexual assault is something no one should experience. but, now people started to voice their experience. it could be something they are not able to speak out 10, 20, 30 years! it is huge that people embrace what happened and actually talk about it. can you image something like that happened in your life and you just canâ€™t talked about it? how would that impact your life? what your life would be?

i still remember the day that i made the decision to embrace my metoo story. itâ€™s not because of metoo movement. it is because landmark forum. i have never felt that alive. it definitely a positive thing happened in my life. i had never thought rape happened for me not to me. but now i truly feel that way. 
you never know how it feel if you have not had the experience. even you do, you would never feel how i feel...so you never know! 
the most challenge that i have is people look at me and have the facial expression showing poor thing. i donâ€™t know about other survivors. for me, i donâ€™t like it. it feels like you look at a disability people and saying poor you. it is what it is. nothing we can change. yes it is out of norm. but whatâ€™s the norm? norm is majority people. the minority does not mean it is bad. it just means less. however, i donâ€™t blame on peopleâ€™s reactions because it is a rare thing (hmm...it actually seems very common when people start talking about it) and people never learned how to properly react to it. i believe it is part of survivorsâ€™ responsibility to educate the society how you like to be treated. from my personal experience, the best way to support survivors is no judgment. be present when we need emotional support. simple! 
if more people can look at metoo movement as a chance for  survivors to embrace the moment and for non-survivors to learn how to be supportive. we will have more love in this planet. and the movement actually is toward positivity!

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
take back control. 
having faced many tough challenges and traumas in my own life i know how hard it is to keep moving forwards, when you are stuck in the past, to lift yourself up when you are in the depths of anxiety and despair, to imagine a better future when your past has been traumatic and chaotic. ğŸ’•
ğŸ’•
i know. i have been there. ğŸ’•
ğŸ’•
i might not have looked like a survivor of some pretty crap life challenges and traumas to everyone i knew and who knew me. because to the outside world i kept it together. just about!  yet inside i was often very broken. ğŸ’•
ğŸ’•
my way of dealing with it all wasnâ€™t better or worse, it was just my way of coping. ğŸ’•
ğŸ’•
i have learned how to take back control of my own life. to look into my amazing future and design my own destiny. not the destiny defined by my past. ğŸ’•
ğŸ’•
let me help you to do the same. let me help you set amazing goals, redefine your beliefs and step, magnificently, into your desired future.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency
