text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
nigerian author #chimamandangoziadichie was featured on the cover of the october 27 issue of #telegraphmagazine, where she discussed nigeria, misogyny, and the #metoo movement.

chimamanda talked about losing faith in nigeria after her father was kidnapped in 2015, how she feels he was kidnapped because of her.

she said:

it was because of me. that incident affected my father â€“ it robbed him of something; thereâ€™s a distrust that he didnâ€™t have before. he comes from a generation with a certain kind of integrity. for a long time he didnâ€™t understand things like bribery â€“ it just perplexed him. my father had given his everything â€“ he got his phd in the us and he had job offers there in the 1960s, but he was keen to come back to nigeria. it was post-independence, everyone was very enthusiastic and my father spent his life teaching. i felt that nigeria had failed him â€“ for a man of his age to be thrown into the boot of a car â€¦that incident broke my heart and itâ€™s the first time i started to seriously question nigeria.

the cover story is up on the telegraph website.
.

text:
the more i see articles about this poor girl in ireland whose underwear was used as evidence in her trial against a 27 year old man who raped her, the more angry i get. the defence is quoted as saying "you have to look at the way she was dressed. she way wearing a lace front thong." i am still just shocked that this is considered actual evidence in a 21st century court room. we are talking about a girls undergarments. this is something that goes under clothes. it's not like this was all she was wearing. even if it was, that is no excuse for an almost 30 year old man's actions. i think about the few times i have been in situations i didnt want to be and what i was wearing. i wasn't wearing anything promiscuous, a skirt that ended at my knees, a cheerleading uniform, once even a heavy winter coat the went to my thighs. clothing is not the problem. the problem is men who think that they have a right to use that as an excuse. the problem is men who don't view women as humans, but objects. the problem is our court system. the problem is that a young man with a good record can get off easy for destroying a young womans life simply because he "has his whole life ahead of him". this is just purely ludicrous in my brain. i truly can not wrap my head around the fact that this happened. my heart goes out to that poor survivor and all the other survivors, those who speak out and live in silence. this is a truly unjust world we live in. this is our time. as we rise up, we make strides, both individually and together as women. this is our time. â¤

#clothingisnotconsent #metoo
name: Ellorah Simmons
tweet_full:
the more i see articles about this poor girl in ireland whose underwear was used as evidence in her trial against a 27 year old man who raped her, the more angry i get. the defence is quoted as saying "you have to look at the way she was dressed. she way wearing a lace front thong." i am still just shocked that this is considered actual evidence in a 21st century court room. we are talking about a girls undergarments. this is something that goes under clothes. it is not like this was all she was wearing. even if it was, that is no excuse for an almost 30 year old man's actions. i think about the few times i have been in situations i didnt want to be and what i was wearing. i wasn't wearing anything promiscuous, a skirt that ended at my knees, a cheerleading uniform, once even a heavy winter coat the went to my thighs. clothing is not the problem. the problem is men who think that they have a right to use that as an excuse. the problem is men who do not view women as humans, but objects. the problem is our court system. the problem is that a young man with a good record can get off easy for destroying a young womans life simply because he "has his whole life ahead of him". this is just purely ludicrous in my brain. i truly can not wrap my head around the fact that this happened. my heart goes out to that poor survivor and all the other survivors, those who speak out and live in silence. this is a truly unjust world we live in. this is our time. as we rise up, we make strides, both individually and together as women. this is our time. â¤

#clothingisnotconsent #metoo

text:
day 315. another woman was violently killed in australia two days ago, witches. maria van beers, aged 63, was allegedly stabbed to death by her ex-husband in tweed heads. worst of all, sheâ€™d just appealed for help and had just the previous day taken out an avo against him. 
how fucking terrified must poor maria have been. and how fucking alone. did you hear about her horrific death? no? itâ€™s not surprising. unless you follow sites like the red heart campaign who document these murders, or unless you live locally where this was well reported, you wouldnâ€™t know. we found some local sites and a channel 9 link, but apart from that, fucking *crickets*. at the risk of sounding like stuck fucking records, we once again bring up the fucking bullshit hypocrisy here. if a shark attack had occurred anywhere in the country a few days ago, it wouldâ€™ve been front page fucking news. if a muslim had killed someone itâ€™d be the first 10 pages and the number one tv news report. if another needle had been found in any kind of fruit, weâ€™d be sick of fucking hearing about it. and not only the reporting, but the fucking money thrown at fixing it. nothing too much trouble. no fucking expense spared. and no politician unwilling to smirk at a camera for extra brownie points. 
women. stabbed, strangled, drowned, raped, burned, shot, gassed or bludgeoned. with or without their children. by partners or strangers. terrorised for years or taken by surprise. young or old, attractive or not, disabled or not, rich or poor or middling, gay or straight, partnered or not, happy, sad, mothers, non-mothers. all valuable. all special. all alive, until they werenâ€™t. all suffering intense fear and pain, until it stopped. and almost all killed by men both known and unknown to them. 
weâ€™ll say it again: lock the fucking men up till they find a way to prove weâ€™re safe from them. lock them up before one more woman fucking dies. lock them up because why the fuck are they free while women - all women - must be careful? #lockupthemen #metoo

text:
part 2 
coming out of the trauma of the abuse was a struggle. i continued having moments of guilt; where i felt like i abandoned something or someone that could have been fixed. i started seeing a psychiatrist and was diagnosed with mixed anxiety depression. i was slowly beginning to realize that i was surrounded by people who actually loved me and cared about me. i realized what i had been missing and how completely messed up my idea of love was. i started doing the things i loved and started to focus on myself and my work again. i feel no guilt toward the relationship anymore and donâ€™t miss it at all. with everything that has happened, i can say, i have never before felt so content with myself. â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸
amaaya is currently focusing on their art, getting back to college and helping people that have been through similar things. they organize events that provided a safe space for people to share their experiences in a creative environment. they are also an active part of the â€˜metooâ€™ movement and are helping women who have come to them with their experiences. *amaaya has recently come out as non-binary and has switched pronouns to they/them. â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸â–«ï¸
interviewed by sruthi chaithanya, counselling psychologist, muktha foundation

text:
abused children need to regain and feel like they have control. this will give them confidence in themselves, certainty in the situation, and a knowing that they are not being controlled. it is a simple choice to most but everything to them. letting them dress themselves including picking out the clothes, choosing between 2 options for a meal, activity, or movie. keep it simple overwhelming with to many choices will have the opposite effect.

#parentingtips #momswhoprotect #momlife #dadlife #parentingtheabused #childabuse #stopchildabuse #childsexualabuse #children #childabuseawareness #metoo

text:
oh man. the worst years of my life - #collegeyears. i hated it so much that every day passed with me wishing that it either burns down or gets blasted away into space.
.
moving from calcutta to hyderabad from a co-ed school to an all-girls college, it was a very troubling time for the rebel in me. in fact so troubling that i was called into principal's office few times and was even suspended once. for, well, saying "baap ki jaagir hai" to my qt teacher, when she threw away (lit.) my project on the face as she felt it was incomplete and also, shouting that #imma get my class (or home) teacher arrested if he dares to touch me again. ohhhh yep, my quite embarrassed mom was called into the principal's office.
.
before i turned into a goody person (thank you @callouscoder), a bunch of us used to bunk college and hang out at our #adda imax, as we used to call it (than prasad's). eating mcds and followed around getting eve-teased by guys who had nothing better to do in their lives. but, what was cringey that some of the girls were actually asking for it. gaahh, that used to repulse me a lot and eventually becoming one of the reasons to ban me from the group.
.
in the first pic, i am standing near ladies washroom of imax, wearing one of my younger brother's t-shirt that i stole quite forcibly as i fell in love with it and an army cargo pant as i wanted to make a statement: #dontmesswithme.
.
the second picture is of the stage where my worst nightmare played out. #mycollege.
.
maybe it had to do with cultural shock, or coming from a very repressing religious background or both, most of my growing up time was troubled. there are other issues as well that will probably fall under #metoo, #bodyshaming or #mentalhealth category, and are for another time.
.
#throwback #throwbacktocollegedays #worstdays #tenyearsago #decade #rebelinme #rebellious #womenpower #weshallovercome #fightlikeagirl

text:
part 3/3
#metoo :
year 2013, i fell into this trap of a toxic relationship. he was a senior in my college. and he had the nerves to do this thing what you can see in this video. to stamp on my soul. i was so happy to be getting to showcase my hobby in the freshers of 2014, i was practicing so much with @tejaswanibhargava @anamhashmi27 @priyajain0812 @surabhisharma699 for the success. but he then came and scolded, abused and used such bad words to refer to my talent, i can't even write that. he didn't want me to dance so he tried every possible way to stop me. mental and physical abuse, he went to that extent. he took me to a corner n almost thrashed me while his own friends were complimenting me. 
days passed by, torture was on its increasing spree. i was condemned to use fb, insta and had to cut off contacts with every friend around me. and i kept accepting with idk what fear. i had nothing but to think of him and talk to him. he blocked all my senses. and then, he suddenly lost interest in me. he stopped responding me, everywhere. it tortured me more. i started having ocd since then. i tried investigating and hacked his skype account finally. and lo n behold!  i saw him sending adult things to his ex. when confronted, he wasn't actually sorry for anything. i had chicken pox, was bedridden, he called up just to abuse me with certain words that i've never heard before. i decided then and there to kick him out. i'd be grateful for life to @probir_x07 ,@mohitbajj786  and few more friends for helping me then n there to kick that guy out somehow. 
with this, i put an end to this series ğŸ’•thanks for the love 
#instagood #influencer #inspirationalquotes #mylifestory #lifestyleblogger #delhiblogger #indore #mumbai #stylegram #abusive #soul

text:
as #metooindia continues to dominate our newsfeeds and real lives, the time is now to have a collective dialogue on the huge distance that separates #sexualviolence and access to 'justice' in india.

it's critical that we speak loudly about impunity which prevents this 'justice'. this conversation is too urgent to remain between the covers of our academic titles. so we invite you to be part of #exitimpunity.
zubaan's sexual violence and impunity (svi) project commissioned research on recent histories of sexual violence in #southasia resulting in our svi series of books.Â to take these findings into public discussion and advocacy, two projects â€” body of evidence and stepping stones â€” transform them into #theatre and #slampoetry through script-workshops and performances at universities, law and medical colleges across india and nepal.

in the next few months we'll be chronicling these and holding conversations across our social media channels. we will explore together what exactly impunity is, how it plays out in the medical and legal systems, and how we uphold it in our everyday lives.

stay tuned and join us! tell everyone you know. because #undoingimpunity is too important and needs every last one of us to be fighting.

#respetonaman is a nationwide campaign against gender-based violence. the goal of the project is to spark a sustainable movement across the nation to eliminate all forms of gender-based violence in the philippines through campaigning for awareness, empowerment, and policy.

as inspired by the global #metoo, and #timesup movement and thailandâ€™s #donttellmehowtodress movement, it will focus on bringing the issue into the mainstream and empowering women to rise up against all forms of gender-based violence.

in line with this year's 16-days of activism against gender-based violence, #respetonaman will hold a series of events and programs which would include two big forums, an online campaign, and a localized version of the #donttellmehowtodress exhibit.

#respetonaman is a project of the office of  vp leni robredo, un women safe cities metro manila programme, the embassy of sweden in manila, spark philippines, and empower; supported by don'ttellmehowtodress thailand, cindy sirinya bishop, bdo unibank, sanggunian ng mga paaralang loyola ng ateneo de manila, osci (office of social  concern and involvement of ateneo de manila university), and power plant mall.

text:
#respetonaman is a nationwide campaign against gender-based violence. as inspired by the global #metoo, and #timesup movement and thailandâ€™s #donttellmehowtodress movement, it will focus on bringing the issue into the mainstream and empowering women to rise up against all forms of gender-based violence.

in line with this year's 16-days of activism against gender-based violence, #respetonaman will hold a series of events and programs which would include two big forums, an online campaign, and a philippine version of the #donttellmehowtodress exhibit.

#respetonaman is a project of vice president maria leonor â€œleniâ€ robredo, un women, the embassy of sweden in manila, spark! philippines, and empower; supported by don'ttellmehowtodress thailand, cindy bishop, bdo, sanggunian ng mga paaralang loyola ng ateneo de manila university, office of social concern and involvement of ateneo de manila university, and power plant mall.

text:
m o k i t a: 
what is your mokita? .
â¤ï¸
mokita is a papua new guinean term for something we know about but no one talks about. .
â¤ï¸
papua new guineans measure the health of their tribes by how many mokitas they have. the fewer mokitas, the healthier the tribe.
.
â¤ï¸
in other words, the tribes that can talk about the difficult topics are the most healthy.
.
â¤ï¸
this can apply to mokitas within your family, friendships, workplace and so forth. all these are your â€œtribesâ€. .
â¤ï¸
mokitas are things like mental/physical illness,  sex and sexuality, trauma, emotions, shame, loss of voice, loss/grief, allowing others to step all over our boundaries, menopause,  and so forth. .
â¤ï¸
i think we all have a few mokitas. .
â¤ï¸
i would have to say one of my biggest mokitas was several years ago - the uncovering of past trauma/stress and loss of voice. which i initially never spoke about. to anyone. .
â¤ï¸
yet the more i spoke about it. the more i felt it and released it. the more i healed from it. .
â¤ï¸
and in fact this mokita has became one of the driving forces for the passion in my work with others. .
â¤ï¸
allowing the space to be heard. to share your mokita. to be vulnerable. have a voice. to connect. to feel. to grow. to transform. to be you. and more. .
â¤ï¸
mokita: the truth we all know but agree not to talk about. .
â¤ï¸
what is yours? 
what are you ready to talk about? 
so you too may be healthier. â€¢
â€¢
â€¢

but itâ€™s not an overnight thing to just become fearless is it? iâ€™m in the middle of this healing process and iâ€™m.so.scared! i am almost 7 months out of my last relationship and iâ€™m still battling it. âœ¨
